## 1. What “iOS 26 UX” means for UzaPoint

Apple’s iOS 26 direction centers on **Liquid Glass** (translucent, layered, light-reactive UI), **fluid navigation** (toolbars/tab bars that shrink/expand), **edge-to-edge content**, and **controls that feel physical** (buttons/sliders with depth and motion).

For a **POS app**, you should adopt the **patterns**, not every visual effect on every screen:

| iOS 26 idea | Use on UzaPoint mobile | Limit on POS |
|-------------|------------------------|----------------|
| Liquid Glass nav / tab bar | Bottom bar, headers, sheets | Avoid on product grid behind prices |
| Collapsing tab bar | Main 4-tab shell | Keep POS tab always reachable |
| Morphing toolbar | Inventory, sales list | Checkout: fixed, high-contrast bar |
| In-place confirmation | Settings toggles, small actions | Payment result: full screen |
| Edge-to-edge lists | Dashboard, inventory | Cart totals: solid card |
| Spring / fluid motion | Transitions, cart add | No delay on “Pay” tap |

**Android** should feel **equally modern** (Material 3 expressive, blur where supported), not a cheap iOS clone — same colors, spacing, and components, with **platform-appropriate** navigation gestures and back behavior.

