## 2. Your web palette (source of truth)

`Frontend_Web` already defines a **neutral, monochrome** system in OKLCH — ideal for cross-platform sync:

| Token | Role (light mode) | Notes |
|-------|-------------------|--------|
| `background` | App canvas | Near white |
| `foreground` | Text, logo “U” block | Near black |
| `primary` | Buttons, emphasis | Dark gray (~black) |
| `primary-foreground` | Text on primary | Near white |
| `secondary` / `muted` | Surfaces, hints | Light gray |
| `muted-foreground` | Secondary text | Mid gray |
| `border` / `input` | Dividers, fields | Light border |
| `destructive` | Errors, void/refund | Red-orange |
| `chart-1` … `chart-5` | Analytics only | Keep identical on mobile charts |
| `radius` | **10px** (`0.625rem`) | Cards, buttons, inputs |
| Dark mode | Full parallel set in `.dark` | Match web toggle |

Brand mark on web: **“U” on `foreground` / `background` invert** — reuse that on mobile splash, login, app icon.

**Recommendation:** Add one shared artifact (no code here — just process):

- `design-tokens/uzapoint_tokens.json` (or YAML) with all OKLCH values + radii + spacing  
- Web imports it (or documents hex/OKLCH copy)  
- Flutter `ThemeExtension` reads the same file at build time  

That prevents “mobile gray ≠ web gray” drift.

**Fonts:** Web uses **Geist**. Mobile: **Inter** or **Geist** via font package if licensed; fallback **SF Pro / Roboto** for system harmony on each OS while keeping **sizes and weights** aligned (e.g. title 22 semibold, body 15 regular).

